Let $A = \arccos x,$ $B = \arccos 2x,$ and $C = \arccos 3x.$ Then $A + B + C = \pi,$ so $A + B = \pi - C,$ and $\cos (A + B) = \cos (\pi - C).$ Thus, $\cos A \cos B - \sin A \sin B = - \cos C.$ This gives us
\begin{align*} x(2x) - \sqrt{1 - x^2} \sqrt{1 - 4x^2} &= -3x \\ 2x^2 + 3x &= \sqrt{1 - x^2} \sqrt{1 - 4x^2} \end{align*}Squaring both sides, we obtain
\begin{align*} (2x^2 + 3x)^2 &= (1 - x^2)(1 - 4x^2) \\ 4x^4 + 12x^3 + 9x^2 &= 1 - 5x^2 + 4x^4 \\ 12x^3 + 14x^2 - 1 &= 0 \end{align*}Then $a = 12,$ $b = 14,$ $c = 0,$ and $d = -1.$
Then $|a| + |b| + |c| + |d| = |12| + |14| + |0| + |-1| = 12 + 14 + 0 + 1 = 27.$

We have $12x^3 + 14x^2 - 1 = 0.$ Then $x$ must be positive. If $x = \frac{1}{4},$ then $12 \cdot \frac{1}{64} + 14 \cdot \frac{1}{16} - 1 = \frac{3}{16} + \frac{14}{16} - 1 = \frac{17}{16} - 1 = \frac{1}{16} > 0.$
If $x = \frac{1}{5},$ then $12 \cdot \frac{1}{125} + 14 \cdot \frac{1}{25} - 1 = \frac{12}{125} + \frac{70}{125} - 1 = \frac{82}{125} - 1 = -\frac{43}{125} < 0.$
Then there is a root between $\frac{1}{5}$ and $\frac{1}{4}.$

Let $f(x) = \arccos x + \arccos 2x + \arccos 3x.$ We require that $3x \le 1,$ so $x \le \frac{1}{3}.$
If $\arccos x + \arccos 2x + \arccos 3x = \pi,$ then $\arccos 2x + \arccos 3x = \pi - \arccos x,$ so
\begin{align*} \cos (\arccos 2x + \arccos 3x) &= \cos(\pi - \arccos x) \\ (2x)(3x) - \sqrt{1 - (2x)^2} \sqrt{1 - (3x)^2} &= -x \\ 6x^2 + x &= \sqrt{(1 - 4x^2)(1 - 9x^2)} \end{align*}Squaring both sides, we obtain
\begin{align*} (6x^2 + x)^2 &= (1 - 4x^2)(1 - 9x^2) \\ 36x^4 + 12x^3 + x^2 &= 1 - 13x^2 + 36x^4 \\ 12x^3 + 14x^2 - 1 &= 0 \end{align*}Then $a = 12,$ $b = 14,$ $c = 0,$ $d = -1,$ so $|a| + |b| + |c| + |d| = 12 + 14 + 0 + 1 = 27.$

If $x = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{6},$ then
\begin{align*} 12x^3 + 14x^2 - 1 &= 12 \left( \frac{\sqrt{2}}{6} \right)^3 + 14 \left( \frac{\sqrt{2}}{6} \right)^2 - 1 \\ &= 12 \cdot \frac{2 \sqrt{2}}{216} + 14 \cdot \frac{2}{36} - 1 \\ &= \frac{24 \sqrt{2}}{216} + \frac{28}{36} - 1 \\ &= \frac{\sqrt{2}}{9} + \frac{7}{9} - 1 = \frac{\sqrt{2} + 7 - 9}{9} = \frac{\sqrt{2} - 2}{9} \approx \frac{1.414 - 2}{9} < 0. \end{align*}If $x = \frac{1}{4},$ then $12x^3 + 14x^2 - 1 = 12 \cdot \frac{1}{64} + 14 \cdot \frac{1}{16} - 1 = \frac{3}{16} + \frac{14}{16} - 1 = \frac{17}{16} - 1 = \frac{1}{16} > 0.$

Consider $4x^2 + 2x - 1 = 0,$ i.e. $x \approx 0.3.$

$12x^3 + 14x^2 - 1 = 0.$  Here, $|a| + |b| + |c| + |d| = 12 + 14 + 0 + 1 = 27.$

From $6x^2 + x = \sqrt{(1 - 4x^2)(1 - 9x^2)}$, we must have $x > 0.$
However, we can have the other expression, $6x^2 + x = - \sqrt{(1 - 4x^2)(1 - 9x^2)}$. In this case, by squaring etc, you would get the same cubic.

