Let $(a_1, a_2, \dots, a_n)$ be a sequence of positive real numbers. Then
$\sum_{i = 1}^n a_i = 96, \quad \sum_{i = 1}^n a_i^2 = 144, \quad \sum_{i = 1}^n a_i^3 = 216$.
By Cauchy-Schwarz inequality, $(\sum_{i=1}^n a_i^2)^2 \le (\sum_{i=1}^n a_i)(\sum_{i=1}^n a_i^3)$.
Thus $144^2 \le (96)(216)$ which is $20736 \le 20736$.
Thus the equality holds. Then $a_1=a_2=...=a_n=k$.
Then $nk=96$, $nk^2=144$, $nk^3 = 216$.
$\frac{nk^2}{nk} = \frac{144}{96} = \frac{3}{2}$, $k = \frac{3}{2}$.
Then $\frac{nk^3}{nk^2} = \frac{216}{144} = \frac{3}{2}$, $k = \frac{3}{2}$.
$nk = 96$ becomes $n\left(\frac{3}{2}\right) = 96$.
$n = \frac{2 \cdot 96}{3} = 2\cdot 32 = 64$. Only one value of n. The sum is $64$.

